And now the story isn‚Äôt mine anymore‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs all yours. ü§ç

The Tortured Poets Department. An anthology of new works that reflect events, opinions and sentiments from a fleeting and fatalistic moment in time - one that was both sensational and sorrowful in equal measure. This period of the author‚Äôs life is now over, the chapter closed and boarded up. There is nothing to avenge, no scores to settle once wounds have healed. And upon further reflection, a good number of them turned out to be self-inflicted. This writer is of the firm belief that our tears become holy in the form of ink on a page. Once we have spoken our saddest story, we can be free of it.

And then all that‚Äôs left behind is the tortured poetry.

Like many of you, I watched the debate tonight. If you haven‚Äôt already, now is a great time to do your research on the issues at hand and the stances these candidates take on the topics that matter to you the most. As a voter, I make sure to watch and read everything I can about their proposed policies and plans for this country.

Recently I was made aware that AI of ‚Äòme‚Äô falsely endorsing Donald Trump‚Äôs presidential run was posted to his site. It really conjured up my fears around AI, and the dangers of spreading misinformation. It brought me to the conclusion that I need to be very transparent about my actual plans for this election as a voter. The simplest way to combat misinformation is with the truth.

I will be casting my vote for Kamala Harris and Tim Walz in the 2024 Presidential Election. I‚Äôm voting for @kamalaharris because she fights for the rights and causes I believe need a warrior to champion them. I think she is a steady-handed, gifted leader and I believe we can accomplish so much more in this country if we are led by calm and not chaos. I was so heartened and impressed by her selection of running mate @timwalz, who has been standing up for LGBTQ+ rights, IVF, and a woman‚Äôs right to her own body for decades.

I‚Äôve done my research, and I‚Äôve made my choice. Your research is all yours to do, and the choice is yours to make. I also want to say, especially to first time voters: Remember that in order to vote, you have to be registered! I also find it‚Äôs much easier to vote early. I‚Äôll link where to register and find early voting dates and info in my story.

With love and hope,

We have officially wrapped the European leg of The Eras Tour. With it came the most passionate crowds I‚Äôve ever played for, new traditions in the show, and an entirely new era added in. It was a more hectic pace than we‚Äôd done before, and I‚Äôm so proud of my crew/fellow performers for being able to physically perform that show and build our massive stage, take it apart, and make magic with so few days in between for recovery and travel. They‚Äôre the most impressive people I know and I‚Äôm so lucky they gave The Eras Tour their time, their energy, and their expertise.
Walking onstage in London was a rollercoaster of emotions. Having our Vienna shows cancelled was devastating. The reason for the cancellations filled me with a new sense of fear, and a tremendous amount of guilt because so many people had planned on coming to those shows. But I was also so grateful to the authorities because thanks to them, we were grieving concerts and not lives. I was heartened by the love and unity I saw in the fans who banded together. I decided that all of my energy had to go toward helping to protect the nearly half a million people I had coming to see the shows in London. My team and I worked hand in hand with stadium staff and British authorities every day in pursuit of that goal, and I want to thank them for everything they did for us. Let me be very clear: I am not going to speak about something publicly if I think doing so might provoke those who would want to harm the fans who come to my shows. 
In cases like this one, ‚Äòsilence‚Äô is actually showing restraint, and waiting to express yourself at a time when it‚Äôs right to. My priority was finishing our European tour safely, and it is with great relief that I can say we did that.
And then London felt like a beautiful dream sequence. All five crowds at Wembley Stadium were bursting with passion, joy, and exuberance. The energy in that stadium was like the most giant bear hug from 92,000 people each night, and it brought me back to a place of carefree calm up there.

Oh I loved those Warsaw shows SO much!!! Our first time ever playing in Poland, but it won‚Äôt be the last... I seriously had the best time üòÜ Also want to thank those beautiful crowds for making us the first tour to play 3 nights in a row in your stadium!! I can‚Äôt believe we have 2 cities left on the European leg of The Eras Tour. It‚Äôs truly flown by.  See you üîú Vienna!

Christmas S‚Äômores Cookies üî•üç™ 

RECIPE:
- 1/2 cup unsalted melted butter
- 1/2 cup of light brown sugar
- 1/3 cup granulated sugar
- 1 large egg (room temp)
- 1 tablespoon of vanilla extract
- 1 1/4 cup of flour
- 1/2 teaspoon baking soda
- 1 pinch of sea salt
- 1 cup semi sweet chips
- graham crackers
- mini marshmallows

DIRECTIONS:
1- pre-heat oven to 350 & line baking sheet with parchment paper
2- mix flour, baking soda, & salt
3- in another bowl, whisk together butter, brown sugar, granulated sugar, & egg until a paste forms
4- slowly fold in dry ingredients into the wet until combined
5- fold in chocolate chips
6- arrange the graham crackers on the baking sheet, top with chocolate wafers, a few mini marshmallows and spoonful of cookie dough
7- bake for 12-15 minutes
8- enjoy!

Hosted a beautiful ceremony last night with my girlfriends in honor of the full moon in Aries ‚ôàÔ∏è‚ú® 

We kicked off the evening with a yummy dinner, then gathered around Jill (@spiritdaughter), who shared the significance of this powerful full moon. She led us through a grounding meditation, followed by a fire release ceremony üî• and clearing. We each wrote down anything holding us back and released it into the fire ‚Äì a ritual used across cultures to symbolize transformation, letting go, and purification.

Feeling so grateful for nights like these and friendships where we can hold space for one another ü´∂üèΩ The energy of this new moon will continue until Saturday night, so take advantage of it! More info from @spiritdaughter below ü§ç

‚ÄúFull of passion and fire, Aries connects us with our warrior spirit. This Moon is a window into your life‚Äôs purpose and soul‚Äôs path. It has the potential to catapult you to your next great adventure and is an invitation to break through something you‚Äôve been processing for weeks or even months.

As you journey through this empowering Moon, feel what you need to release or burn away to align with your true passion. Feel what distracts or makes you doubt yourself. Understand what keeps you small or makes you question your abilities. Then, align with Aries to shift, transform, and release these energies. Take back your power from anything, or anyone, who has disempowered you. Then run towards the things that light you up inside.

This Moon brings us much energy. Notice if frustration, anger, restlessness, or impatience rises over this Moon and move your body to work with these emotions. Channel this excess energy into something. Take a bold step, try something new, or commit your energy towards something this week. Don‚Äôt, though, make a decision in haste just to make one. If you feel scattered, ground your energy through movement or breathwork. Once you feel clear, commit to what feels most aligned with who you are.‚Äù

JOHN LEGEND // HARPER‚ÄôS BAZAAR MEN CHINA

Over the years, John and I have collaborated on countless photoshoots‚Äîeditorials, lifestyle, and brand campaigns. But this one? Has to be one of my must proud.

John has always trusted me to bring my vision to life, and for this shoot, I set out to create something fresh, something different from everything we‚Äôve done before.

Inspired by the iconic heroic images of James Bond, I wanted to capture John as the modern embodiment of 007. From the sleek, timeless look of Roger Moore‚Äôs red carnation in a white suit to the vintage Porsche, every frame was designed to evoke that signature Bond attitude. With his own unique style and charisma, John made it his own and  brought my vision to life.

Not only that it is the first issue to usher in the new year of 2025. It is also released on his birthday. 

Happy Birthday John

It‚Äôs hard to believe it‚Äôs been two decades since we made Get Lifted. This album is very meaningful to me. It was the culmination of years of work, and it started John‚Äôs career as an artist, and my career as a producer and songwriter. 

Working on the bonus material for the anniversary edition brought back a lot of memories. Reflecting on that period, I see that John and I were very focused on music, worked extremely hard, and were hungry to be great. Two decades later, when I hear the music we made in that era, I can hear how much we were absorbing the various musical influences that we loved and how they informed my developing production style. But maybe what stands out the most is the songwriting. John and I worked together for several years before the release of Get Lifted, and I‚Äôm reminded how much we developed our songwriting chops in that period; I think we‚Äôre in full bloom on Get Lifted. 

It‚Äôs immensely rewarding that so many people have enjoyed this music. And now everyone can enjoy the additional bonus tracks as well! 

Congrats on this milestone, @johnlegend. And thanks for the continued memories.

Dave

I remember being obsessed with this song "Refuge" as a kid. Full disclosure - I was actually obsessed with the entire album. So of course it was my complete pleasure to be featured on this one by the legendary @johnlegend üåº #happy20th

On December 28, 2004, my 26th birthday, I released my debut album Get Lifted. Get Lifted, like any artist's debut, was the culmination of years of practice, development, writing songs, making demos, playing poorly attended gigs, getting rejected by gatekeepers, until those nos finally turned to "YES." As we approach the 20th anniversary of this album, the music that introduced me to the world, I just want to say THANK YOU. Thank you to everyone who contributed, believed in me, supported me, listened to me, came to see me in concert over the years. 

I meet many of you as I travel the world. I hear your stories about the first time you heard "Ordinary People" and how it helped you get through a rough spot in your relationship. I hear about you proposing to your spouse with "Stay With You" or "All of Me," dancing to "Green Light" or "Tonight," marching to "Glory," celebrating the holidays to A Legendary Christmas or walking down the aisle to "You & I" or "So High". Thanks for letting me be a part of these moments in your lives.

We've been working on some really special ways to celebrate 20 years of Get Lifted, including a 20th Anniversary Edition of the album which features all the original songs, plus all-new remixes featuring some of my favorite artists, along with some unreleased demos from the early 2000s.

I love my life. I love pouring my soul into this music and sharing it with you. I had big dreams for myself when I was a kid growing up in Springfield, Ohio, but what has actually happened has been beyond my wildest of dreams. Thank you all for 20 magical years.

I think a lot about the relationship I have with my own inner demons. It‚Äôs never been easy for me to face how I get seduced by chaos and turmoil. It makes me feel claustrophobic.

Disease is about facing that fear, facing myself and my inner darkness, and realizing that sometimes I can‚Äôt win or escape the parts of myself that scare me. That I can try and run from them but they are still part of me and I can run and run but eventually I‚Äôll meet that part of myself again, even if only for a moment. 

Dancing, morphing, running, purging. Again and again, back with myself. This integration is ultimately beautiful to me because it‚Äôs mine and I‚Äôve learned to handle it. I am the conductor of my own symphony.  I am every actor in the plays¬†that are my art and my life. No matter how scary the question, the answers are inside of me. Essential, inextricable parts of what makes me me. I save myself by keeping going. I am the whole me, I am strong, and I am up for the challenge. Happy Halloween.

At this year‚Äôs @ObamaFoundation Democracy Forum, I spoke about pluralism ‚Äì the idea that in a democracy, we all have to find a way to live alongside individuals and groups who are different from us. So we commit to a system of rules that helps us peacefully resolve our disputes and try to cultivate habits that encourage us to not only tolerate each other but also join in collective action. 

I‚Äôm convinced if we want democracy as we understand it to survive, then we‚Äôre all going to have to work towards a renewed commitment to pluralism. The alternative is what we‚Äôve seen here in the U.S. and in many democracies around the world ‚Äì not just gridlock and public cynicism, but an increasing willingness on the part of politicians and their followers to violate democratic norms, use the power of the state to target critics, journalists or political rivals and even resort to violence in order to gain and hold on to power.

There are no easy answers. Some of the problems we‚Äôre seeing have played out over decades, and reversing them is going to take time as well. But we are seeing successful efforts by young leaders around this country and around the world to reinvigorate pluralist values. 

And what those leaders are discovering is that, when they listen to people and recognize their multiple identities and seek out common experiences and common values ‚Äì they‚Äôre not just strengthening democratic habits. They‚Äôre also building stronger organizations and delivering better results for their members. 

That‚Äôs the power of pluralism. That‚Äôs how we‚Äôll reduce the cynicism that is so prevalent in our politics right now. And ultimately, that‚Äôs how we‚Äôll work together to solve the greatest challenges of our time.

Hi, my name is Nika Kovaƒç and I‚Äôll be joining President Obama tomorrow at the @ObamaFoundation Democracy Forum in Chicago. Today I‚Äôll be sharing my story. 

I want to start off by saying that I know the last couple of months have been hard. There has been a lot of anxiety and uncertainty around us. So I hope my story ‚Äì a story about a group of girls from Slovenia who decided to change the world ‚Äì will inspire you to take action around causes important to you in your own community. 

Over the years, my team at The Research Institute of 8th March in Slovenia have helped unite people across political views, ages, and religions to lead impactful campaigns. Together, we‚Äôve protected clean water, removed political interference from public media, secured free school lunches, and more. 

Right now we are coordinating a movement in Europe to help protect reproductive rights. 

I was an Obama Scholar in New York when the U.S. Supreme Court took away reproductive rights from women. One thought filled my mind: This must not happen in Europe. So I decided to lead a campaign to prevent this. And through the @ObamaFoundation Leaders Europe Program, I realized my community extends far beyond the borders of my country. Many of my closest friends are from this program, and when I launched a European campaign to support safe and accessible abortion, they stood by me. 

Now we are close to collecting the one million signatures we need for the @myvoicemychoiceorg initiative ‚Äì a European Citizens‚Äô Initiative that will make sure that every person in Europe will have access to safe abortions. Our supporters have been remarkably diverse: they are grandparents, students, even people leaving church on Sunday. Every single one of them gives me hope ‚Äì and these days, we need hope more than ever. ‚Äì@NikaKolac

We‚Äôve been through a lot in the last few years, and many folks may not feel like this is the best time to talk about democracy. But I think this is exactly the right time to talk about it. 

Over the last couple of years, we‚Äôve talked about two of the major factors eroding democracy: the change in how we get information, and how a shifting economy makes a growing number of people feel like they don‚Äôt have control over their own economic fates.

But there‚Äôs a third element to this, which is how in a country as diverse as ours we can set up rules and habits that allow us to disagree deeply while still finding a way to live together.

This idea ‚Äì called pluralism ‚Äì will be the focus of the @ObamaFoundation‚Äôs third annual Democracy Forum on December 5. I‚Äôll share more of my thoughts then ‚Äì and I hope you‚Äôll tune in. Check out the link in my bio for more details.

Over the last few weeks and through Election Day, millions of Americans cast their votes ‚Äì not just for president, but for leaders at every level. Now the results are in, and we want to congratulate President Trump and Senator Vance on their victory.
 
This is obviously not the outcome we had hoped for, given our profound disagreements with the Republican ticket on a whole host of issues. But living in a democracy is about recognizing that our point of view won‚Äôt always win out, and being willing to accept the peaceful transfer of power.
 
Michelle and I could not be prouder of Vice President Harris and Governor Walz ‚Äì two extraordinary public servants who ran a remarkable campaign. And we will always be grateful to the staff and volunteers who poured their heart and soul into electing public servants they truly believed in. 
 
As I said on the campaign trail, America has been through a lot over the last few years ‚Äì from a historic pandemic and price hikes resulting from the pandemic, to rapid change and the feeling a lot of folks have that, no matter how hard they work, treading water is the best they can do. Those conditions have created headwinds for democratic incumbents around the world, and last night showed that America is not immune. 
 
The good news is that these problems are solvable ‚Äì but only if we listen to each other, and only if we abide by the core constitutional principles and democratic norms that made this country great.
 
In a country as big and diverse as ours, we won‚Äôt always see eye-to-eye on everything. But progress requires us to extend good faith and grace ‚Äì even to people with whom we deeply disagree. That‚Äôs how we‚Äôve come this far, and it‚Äôs how we‚Äôll keep building a country that is more fair and more just, more equal and more free.
